Explanation:

- The API route is defined in routes/api.php: Route::delete('/posts/{post}/likes', [App\Http\Controllers\Api\V1\PostLikeController::class, 'destroy']). That means the API DELETE /v1/posts/{post}/likes is handled by App\Http\Controllers\Api\V1\PostLikeController::destroy.
- The Api\V1\PostLikeController::destroy implementation simply returns $post->dislike().
- The Likeable trait's dislike() calls $this->likes()->where('author_id', auth()->id())->get()->each->delete() — which returns a collection (array) of Like model instances (after deletion). The Like model and migration show the model fields: id, likeable_id, likeable_type, author_id, created_at, updated_at.
- Tests (tests/Feature/Api/V1/PostLikeTest.php) assert that an authenticated DELETE request returns HTTP 200 (assertOk).
- The route group applies 'auth:sanctum' middleware; unauthenticated requests will yield 401 responses from the API.
- If the {post} resource is not found, typical Laravel behavior is to return a 404 response.

Based on the above, the response objects for DELETE /v1/posts/{post}/likes should include:
- 200: success — JSON array of deleted Like objects (each with id, likeable_id, likeable_type, author_id, created_at, updated_at).
- 401: unauthenticated — JSON object with a message string (Laravel default).
- 404: not found — JSON object with a message string.

